# Copy this file to ".env" (next to app.py) and fill in your values, or set
# COPILOT_ENV_FILE to point at an existing .env. The app loads it at startup so
# the Copilot SDK subprocess inherits these. The real .env is gitignored, and
# existing environment variables are never overridden.

# --- Corporate proxy via the Copilot CLI's variables (recommended) -----------
# The app reads these and builds the standard proxy env for you (URL-encoding the
# user/password and setting HTTP(S)_PROXY + NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY / NODE_USE_SYSTEM_CA,
# the same way a run-copilot.ps1 launcher does), so the Node-based copilot binary
# can reach GitHub through the proxy and trust the corporate CA.
# COPILOT_PROXY_USERNAME=your-id
# COPILOT_PROXY_PASSWORD=your-password
# COPILOT_PROXY_HOST=inet-proxy-a.example.net:8080
# NO_PROXY=localhost,127.0.0.1,*.example.com

# NOTE: COPILOT_EXE (used by the Copilot CLI) is intentionally IGNORED by this app.
# A system-installed copilot.exe is often newer than the Python SDK and its
# handshake breaks the SDK ("invalid literal for int()" on ping). The app uses its
# own bundled, protocol-matched binary instead. Only set COPILOT_DESKTOP_CLI if you
# have a binary whose protocol matches github-copilot-sdk:
# COPILOT_DESKTOP_CLI=C:\path\to\matching\copilot.exe

# --- OR set a standard proxy URL directly (takes precedence) -----------------
# HTTPS_PROXY=http://user:password@proxy.example.net:8080
# HTTP_PROXY=http://user:password@proxy.example.net:8080
